            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <b>Air-Source Heat Pumps</b>
              <p>
                Air-source heat pumps are among the most common types and are
                widely used for residential heating and cooling. They operate by
                extracting heat from the outside air and transferring it indoors
                during the winter, and vice versa during the summer. Due to
                their exposure to outdoor elements, they are susceptible to
                issues like refrigerant leaks, compressor failures, and clogged
                filters. Regular maintenance, including cleaning coils and
                checking refrigerant levels, can help mitigate these issues.
                However, if you experience a sudden loss of efficiency or
                unusual noises, it’s crucial to contact a professional
                technician to diagnose and repair the problem promptly.
              </p>

              <b>Ground-Source (Geothermal) Heat Pumps</b>
              <p>
                Ground-source heat pumps, also known as geothermal heat pumps,
                utilize the stable temperature of the ground to provide heating
                and cooling. These systems are highly efficient and
                environmentally friendly but come with their own set of
                complexities. Common repair needs for geothermal systems include
                issues with the underground loops, such as leaks or blockages,
                and problems with the heat exchanger. Given the complexity and
                the specialized nature of these systems, it’s essential to have
                a qualified technician perform any necessary repairs. Regular
                inspections of the loop system and heat exchanger can help
                prevent costly repairs and ensure long-term efficiency.
              </p>

              <b>Water-Source Heat Pumps</b>
              <p>
                Water-source heat pumps operate by exchanging heat with a nearby
                water source, such as a lake, river, or well. These systems are
                particularly efficient in areas where water temperatures remain
                relatively constant throughout the year. However, they can face
                unique challenges such as water contamination, mineral buildup,
                and issues with the water intake system. Regular maintenance,
                including inspecting and cleaning the water intake and discharge
                systems, is crucial for optimal performance. If you notice a
                decline in efficiency or any operational issues, it’s advisable
                to consult with a professional who has experience with
                water-source systems to perform the necessary repairs.
              </p>

              <b>Ductless Mini-Split Heat Pumps</b>
              <p>
                Ductless mini-split heat pumps are ideal for homes without
                ductwork or for adding climate control to specific areas. These
                systems consist of an outdoor unit connected to one or more
                indoor units, providing targeted heating and cooling. Common
                repair needs for ductless systems include refrigerant leaks,
                electrical issues, and problems with the indoor units such as
                fan malfunctions or clogged filters. Regular maintenance,
                including cleaning the filters and checking the refrigerant
                levels, can help prevent these issues. If you experience uneven
                heating or cooling, or if the system fails to turn on, it’s best
                to contact a professional technician to diagnose and repair the
                issue efficiently.
              </p>

              <p>
