                <div class="questions">
                  <p>While there are some basic maintenance tasks you can perform yourself to keep your heat pump running efficiently, certain tasks should be left to professionals to ensure the system operates safely and effectively. Here's a breakdown of what you can do versus when you should hire a professional:</p>
                  <b>DIY Maintenance Tasks:</b>
                  <ol>
                    <li>Regularly Replace or Clean Filters: Dirty filters can significantly reduce the efficiency of your heat pump. Check and replace or clean the filters according to the manufacturer's recommendations, usually every 1-3 months.</li>
                    <li>Clean the Outdoor Unit: Make sure the outdoor unit is free from debris, leaves, and dirt. You can use a garden hose to gently clean the coils, but make sure the unit is turned off before you start.</li>
                    <li>Inspect and Clean the Indoor Unit: Dust and vacuum the indoor unit's air vents and grilles to ensure proper airflow.</li>
                    <li>Check the Thermostat: Ensure your thermostat is functioning correctly and set to the appropriate temperature. Consider upgrading to a programmable thermostat for better energy management.</li>
                    <li>Clear the Area Around the Unit: Make sure there is at least a two-foot clearance around the outdoor unit to ensure proper airflow.</li>
                  </ol>

                  <b>Tasks for a Professional:</b>
                  <ol>
                    <li>Comprehensive System Check: A professional technician can perform a thorough inspection of your heat pump system, including checking refrigerant levels, inspecting electrical connections, and ensuring all components are working correctly.</li>
                    <li>Lubricate Moving Parts: Professionals have the tools and knowledge to properly lubricate bearings and other moving parts, reducing wear and tear.</li>
                    <li>Check and Seal Ductwork: Leaky ducts can reduce efficiency. A professional can inspect and seal any leaks to ensure optimal performance.</li>
                    <li>Test the System's Efficiency: Technicians can use specialized equipment to test the system's efficiency and make necessary adjustments.</li>
                    <li>Diagnose and Repair Issues: If your heat pump is making unusual noises, not heating or cooling properly, or showing any other signs of trouble, a professional can diagnose and fix the issue.</li>
